[2] El Salvador
Date: Fri, 23 Jun 2006 04:24:05 -0400 (EDT)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Prensa Latina, Havana, Cuba, 22 Jun 2006, [edited]
<http://www.plenglish.com/Article.asp?ID=%7B1CAA5E16-9455-4955-8CE7-B537D5CA8B29%7D&language=EN>

Despite the multiple actions carried out in El Salvador to control
the epidemics of dengue, seriously affecting that population,
infection cases increase, revealed Thursday official sources.
Interviewed on the issue Health Minister Guillermo Maza admitted the
speedy increase of infections in the Salvadorian nation.
According to reports released by the State Secretary under his
charge, the country's present conditions are favorable for the
development of the disease.
The national larval index was estimated at 6.1 in March and at 6.5 in
April 2006 while recent controls reflect a 20-percent increase of
infection cases in relation to last week when they similarly raised
in 14 percent.
Public Health authorities confirmed there were 137 infected people
reported to public health centers 11-17 Jun. The week before the
official number was 114.
This virus is mainly transmitted by the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito,
which reproduces in stagnant water and the insalubrious zones where
the poorest population lives.
